ea symbol references when tracing how areas connect.\n\nThe AST tools give you exact signatures, line numbers, and dependency edges. Fall back to `read_file` only when you need to understand the implementation logic (not just the structure).\n\n## Per-File Analysis\n\nFor each file, determine:\n\n- **path**: relative path from repo root\n- **role**: classify as one of: `model`, `controller`, `service`, `utility`, `config`, `test`, `type-definition`, `entry-point`, `middleware`, `migration`, `script`, `template`, `asset`, or a domain-specific role\n- **exports**: list all public functions, classes, constants, or type exports. Use the format `function_name(params) -> return_type` where discernible.\n- **imports_from**: list what this file imports and from where. Use area names when possible (e.g., \"User from data-models\"), otherwise use module paths.\n- **key_functions**: the most important functions/methods with brief signatures and purpose (e.g., `authenticate(credentials) -> Token — validates user credentials`)\n- **patterns**: design patterns observed — singleton, factory, decorator, observer, middleware chain, repository pattern, dependency injection, etc.\n- **summary**: one sentence capturing what this file does and why it exists\n\n## Area Summary\n\nAfter analyzing all files, write a 3-5 sentence **area_summary** covering:\n- The area's overall purpose and responsibility\n- The architectural pattern used (MVC, layered, event-driven, etc.)\n- Key abstractions and how they relate\n- Any notable technical decisions or patterns\n\n## Cross-Area References\n\nList every reference you find to code **outside** your area:\n- Imports from other modules/packages not in your file patterns\n- References to types, functions, or constants defined elsewhere\n- Event emissions or handler registrations that connect to other areas\n\nFormat each as: `imports <symbol> from <other-area-or-module>`\n\n## Suggested Splits\n\nIf your area is too large (>15 files) or contains clearly distinct sub-domains, suggest how it could be split. If it is too small or tightly coupled with another area, suggest a merge. Leave empty if the current boundaries are good.\n\n## Important Constraints\n\n- **Be thorough.** Read every file. Do not skip or skim.\n- **Be concise.** Summaries should capture the essence, not repeat the code. One sentence per file summary. 3-5 sentences for area summary.\n- **Stay in scope.** Only analyze files matching your area's patterns. Note cross-area references but do not read files from other areas.\n- **Be precise about exports and imports.** These feed directly into the relationship mapper. Get function names and module paths right.\n- **Use consistent role labels.** Stick to the role categories listed above.\n\n\n<AVAILABLE_TOOLS>\n- read_file: Read file at _base_dir/path. Returns JSON string.\n- list_directory: List entries at _base_dir/path. Returns JSON string.\n- search_code: Search for regex pattern in files. Returns JSON string.\n- get_file_tree: Walk directory tree and produce indented text. Returns JSON string.\n- code_search: Search code symbols, get source, or get file outlines.\n</AVAILABLE_TOOLS>"
  },
  {
    "role": "user",
    "content": "## Your Area Assignment\n\n**Area:** agentic-rules-skills-workflows\n**Description:** Agentic framework documentation rules, skill definitions, and workflow configurations at the top level.\n**File patterns:** [\"agentic/rules/docs/*.md\", \"agentic/skills/example-skill/SKILL.md\", \"agentic/workflows/example_workflow.json\"]\n\n## Plan Summary\n\nAreas in the plan:\n- spark-core: Core Spark package: initialization, orchestration, configuration, database, UI, and supporting modules that form the main application entry points.\n- spark-engine: Spark's agentic engine: the LLM loop, OpenRouter integration, tool execution, knowledge system, and runner that drives multi-agent documentation generation.\n- spark-agents-and-prompts: Agent definitions (JSON configs) and their corresponding prompt templates (Markdown) that define the behavior of planner, explorer, doc_writer, relationship_mapper, library, and onboarding agents.\n- spark-tools: Tool implementations available to Spark agents: file I/O, code search, library management, plugin installation, database state inspection, and the tool registry/definitions.\n- spark-library: Spark's plugin/library system: catalog of available plugins and library module initialization.\n- spark-templates: Template files that Spark installs into target repositories: .claude config templates, agentic framework templates (engine, tools, rules, skills, workflows), and app-module templates.\n- agentic-engine: The top-level agentic framework (installed instance): engine loop, OpenRouter client, tool executor, knowledge system, and runner.\n- agentic-tools: Tool implementations for the top-level agentic framework: file tree, directory listing, file read/write, code search, and tool definitions.\n- agentic-rules-skills-workflows: Agentic framework documentation rules, skill definitions, and workflow configurations at the top level.\n- claude-config: Claude Code configuration: rules (bug-fixing, invariants, testing), skills (code-documenter, code-search), spark plans, settings, and the rules index.\n- jcodemunch-core: JCodeMunch MCP server core: server entry point, configuration, security, watcher, path mapping, reindex state, and hook events.\n- jcodemunch-parser: JCodeMunch code parser subsystem: symbol extraction, language support, imports analysis, complexity metrics, hierarchy, SQL preprocessing, and context providers (dbt, git blame).\n- jcodemunch-storage: JCodeMunch storage layer: SQLite store, index store, embedding store, and token tracking.\n- jcodemunch-summarizer: JCodeMunch summarization subsystem: file-level and batch summarization of code.\n- jcodemunch-tools: JCodeMunch MCP tool implementations: 40+ analysis tools including search, indexing, dependency graphs, dead code detection, blast radius, refactoring safety checks, and more.\n- jcodemunch-tests: JCodeMunch test suite: 70+ test files covering all tools, parsers, storage, configuration, and integration scenarios.\n- jcodemunch-docs-and-config: JCodeMunch documentation, benchmarks, CI/CD workflows, and project configuration files.\n- root-files-and-templates: Top-level project files (CLAUDE.md, file_merger utility, commands, version marker) and the legacy HTML templates directory for the web UI.\n\n## Instructions\n\nAnalyze all files matching your area's patterns. Return a JSON report with `area`, `files`, `area_summary`, `cross_area_refs`, and optionally `suggested_splits`."
  }
]

