    "role": "tool",
    "tool_call_id": "functions.read_file:8",
    "content": "{\"content\": \"---\\nname: code-documenter\\ndescription: >\\n  Analyses source files, extracts structure, dependencies, and\\n  functionality, then generates or updates documentation rules so that any\\n  developer or agent can understand a file without re-reading the source.\\n  Use this skill when the user says \\\"document this file\\\", \\\"create a rule\\n  about this\\\", \\\"analyse this module\\\", \\\"explain how this works and save it\\\",\\n  \\\"update the rule for X\\\", \\\"we just changed X \\u2014 update the docs\\\",\\n  or any variation of \\\"save what we learned about this code\\\". Also trigger\\n  after any significant code change when the user says \\\"update\\\" or\\n  \\\"sync the docs\\\". This skill manages RULES_INDEX.md files and keeps the\\n  discovery system in sync.\\nallowed-tools:\\n  - Read\\n  - Write\\n  - Bash\\n  - Glob\\n  - Grep\\n  - Edit\\n---\\n\\n# Code Documenter \\u2014 Analyse, Document, and Maintain\\n\\nThis skill has two modes:\\n\\n- **CREATE mode:** Analyse a file or module from scratch, generate a documentation rule, and register it in the index.\\n- **UPDATE mode:** After code changes, refresh an existing documentation rule to stay in sync.\\n\\nThe user triggers CREATE with phrases like \\\"document this\\\", \\\"create a rule about this file\\\", \\\"analyse this and save it\\\".\\nThe user triggers UPDATE with phrases like \\\"update the rule\\\", \\\"sync the docs\\\", \\\"we just changed this \\u2014 update it\\\".\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 1: Determine Mode and Scope\\n\\n1. **Identify the target.** What file or module is the user referring to?\\n   - If they said \\\"this file\\\" \\u2014 check which file was just open or edited in the conversation.\\n   - If they named a path \\u2014 use it directly.\\n   - If they said \\\"what we just worked on\\\" \\u2014 scan the conversation history for the most recently edited files.\\n\\n2. **Determine the mode:**\\n   - No existing rule for this file \\u2192 **CREATE mode** (go to Phase 2)\\n   - Existing rule found \\u2192 **UPDATE mode** (go to Phase 6)\\n\\n3. **Check for an existing rule.** Search for it:\\n   ```\\n   grep -r \\\"<filename or module name>\\\" .claude/RULES_INDEX.md */.claude/RULES_INDEX.md .claude/rules/ */.claude/rules/ 2>/dev/null\\n   ```\\n\\n4. **Identify which module/app this belongs to.** From the file path, determine\\n   the module or app. This determines where the doc rule and index entry go.\\n\\n**Validation Gate:** Confirm the target file exists and you know the module. State the mode (CREATE or UPDATE) before proceeding.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 2: Deep Analysis (CREATE mode)\\n\\nRead the target file fully. Then systematically extract the following.\\n\\n### 2a. Structural Overview\\n\\n- **File type:** Identify what role this file plays (model, controller, service, utility, configuration, worker, test, etc.)\\n- **Patterns used:** List framework-specific patterns and language idioms\\n- **Imports:** List all imports. Group into: standard library, third-party, internal (other project modules)\\n\\n### 2b. Definitions Inventory\\n\\nFor each class, function, or constant defined in the file, extract:\\n\\n| Element | What to capture |\\n|---------|----------------|\\n| **Classes** | Name, base classes, key methods, properties, purpose |\\n| **Functions** | Name, parameters (with types if available), return type, purpose |\\n| **Endpoints/Routes** | Method, path, request/response types, auth requirements |\\n| **Constants/Config** | Name, value/default, where used |\\n| **Types/Interfaces** | Name, fields, where used |\\n\\n### 2c. Dependency Mapping\\n\\nTrace how this file connects to the rest of the system:\\n\\n- **Inbound dependencies** \\u2014 who imports or calls things from this file?\\n  ```\\n  grep -r \\\"from.*<module> import\\\\|import.*<module>\\\" --include=\\\"*.<ext>\\\" -l\\n  ```\\n- **Outbound dependencies** \\u2014 what does this file import from other project modules?\\n- **Data flow participation** \\u2014 which critical flows (from CLAUDE.md) does this module participate in?\\n- **Invariants enforced** \\u2014 which design invariants (from `.claude/rules/invariants.md`) does this module help enforce?\\n\\n### 2d. Impact Analysis\\n\\nFor each major element, write one sentence describing what would break or change if this element were modified. Focus on:\\n\\n- Which other modules import this directly\\n- Which API endpoints expose this\\n- Which data flows would be affected\\n- Which invariants could be violated\\n\\n**Validation Gate:** Present the analysis summary to the user. Ask: \\\"Does this look complete, or should I dig deeper into any area?\\\" Do not generate the rule file until confirmed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 3: Generate the Documentation Rule\\n\\nCreate a markdown rule file that captures everything from Phase 2.\\n\\n### File location and naming convention\\n\\nDocumentation rules live inside the module's `.claude/rules/docs/` folder:\\n\\n```\\n<module>/.claude/rules/docs/<topic>.md\\n```\\n\\nFor cross-module documentation, use the project root:\\n```\\n.claude/rules/docs/<topic>.md\\n```\\n\\n### Required structure of the generated rule\\n\\n```markdown\\n# [Project] \\u2014 [Module Name] Documentation\\n\\n> Auto-generated by code-documenter. Last updated: <YYYY-MM-DD>\\n> Source: `<full file path>`\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\n<2-3 sentences: what this module does and why it exists>\\n\\n## Data Flows\\n\\n<Which critical flows this module participates in>\\n\\n## Invariants Enforced\\n\\n<Which design invariants this module helps enforce, with brief explanation>\\n\\n## Definitions\\n\\n### Functions / Classes\\n\\n#### `function_name` or `ClassName`\\n\\n- **Type:** Service | Model | Endpoint | etc.\\n- **Purpose:** <one sentence>\\n- **Signature:** `def func(param: Type) -> ReturnType`\\n- **Depends on:** <what it imports or calls from other modules>\\n- **Used by:** <which files import or call this \\u2014 file paths>\\n\\n<repeat for each definition>\\n\\n## Module Dependencies\\n\\n| Direction | Module | What | How |\\n|-----------|--------|------|-----|\\n| \\u2192 uses | [module] | [function] | [how it's called] |\\n| \\u2190 used by | [module] | [function] | [how it's called] |\\n\\n## Configuration\\n\\n<What this module reads from config/env. List specific fields.>\\n\\n## Impact Notes\\n\\n<What to be careful about when changing this file.\\nWhich invariants are at risk. Which data flows would be affected.>\\n\\n## Change History\\n\\n| Date | Summary |\\n|------|---------|\\n| <YYYY-MM-DD> | Initial documentation generated |\\n```\\n\\n### Writing guidelines\\n\\n- Keep descriptions factual and terse. No filler.\\n- For \\\"Used by\\\" entries, list file paths not vague descriptions.\\n- Cap the file at 200 lines. Summarise minor elements in a table.\\n- Do NOT paste source code into the rule. Describe structure, don't replicate it.\\n- Always note which invariants the module enforces \\u2014 this is the most important context for safe editing.\\n\\n**Validation Gate:** Write the file, then re-read it and verify every cross-reference file path actually exists.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 4: Register in RULES_INDEX.md\\n\\nFind the `RULES_INDEX.md` for the relevant module:\\n\\n```\\n<module>/.claude/RULES_INDEX.md\\n```\\n\\nIf cross-cutting, use the root `.claude/RULES_INDEX.md`.\\n\\nAdd or update the entry. Each entry is a markdown link with a one-line summary:\\n\\n```markdown\\n- [rules/docs/<module>.md](rules/docs/<module>.md) \\u2014 <one-line summary>\\n```\\n\\nDo not add duplicates. If an entry exists, update its summary.\\n\\n**Validation Gate:** Read the RULES_INDEX.md back and confirm no duplicate entries exist.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 5: Report to User (CREATE mode complete)\\n\\n```\\nDocumentation rule created\\n   File: <path>\\n   Registered in: <RULES_INDEX.md path>\\n\\n   Summary: <2 sentences of what was documented>\\n   Invariants covered: <list which invariants this module enforces>\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 6: Update Existing Rule (UPDATE mode)\\n\\n### 6a. Find the existing rule\\n\\n```\\ngrep -rl \\\"<filename>\\\" .claude/rules/docs/ */.claude/rules/docs/ 2>/dev/null\\n```\\n\\nIf not found, switch to CREATE mode (Phase 2).\\n\\n### 6b. Re-analyse the source file\\n\\nRe-read the source file. Compare against the existing rule:\\n\\n1. **New definitions** \\u2014 functions, classes, endpoints added\\n2. **Removed definitions** \\u2014 things documented that no longer exist\\n3. **Changed signatures** \\u2014 parameters, return types that changed\\n4. **Changed dependencies** \\u2014 new/removed imports\\n5. **Changed data flow participation** \\u2014 new flow involvement\\n6. **Invariant changes** \\u2014 new/removed invariant enforcement\\n\\n### 6c. Apply the delta\\n\\nEdit the existing rule file in place. Do NOT rewrite from scratch. This keeps diffs clean.\\n\\n- Add new definitions, remove deleted ones\\n- Update signatures, dependencies, \\\"Used by\\\" references\\n- Update \\\"Change History\\\" table with today's date\\n- Update the `Last updated` date in the header\\n\\n### 6d. Update RULES_INDEX.md if needed\\n\\nIf the summary or scope changed, update the corresponding entry.\\n\\n### 6e. Report\\n\\n```\\nDocumentation rule updated\\n   File: <path>\\n   Changes:\\n      - Added: <new elements>\\n      - Removed: <deleted elements>\\n      - Updated: <changed elements>\\n   RULES_INDEX.md: <updated / no change needed>\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Phase 7: Batch Mode (optional)\\n\\nIf the user says \\\"document all modules\\\" or \\\"create rules for everything\\\":\\n\\n1. List all source files in scope (excluding tests, configs, init files).\\n2. For each file, run Phase 2\\u20134.\\n3. Review the RULES_INDEX.md for completeness.\\n4. Report a summary.\\n\\nLimit: Process a maximum of 10 files in batch. If more exist, ask the user to prioritise.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Edge Cases\\n\\n- **Init files / barrel exports:** Skip unless they contain significant logic.\\n- **Test files:** Document only if the user explicitly asks.\\n- **Config files (JSON, YAML, TOML):** Document at the project root level, not in a module's docs.\\n- **Very large files (500+ lines):** Cap the rule at 200 lines. Summarise minor elements in a table. Prioritise data flows and invariant enforcement.\\n- **Cross-module functions:** If a function in one module is critical to understanding another, mention it in \\\"Depends on\\\" but don't duplicate its full documentation.\\n\", \"lines\": 293}"
  },
